  "text": "The rank K = 3 classification largely preserved the K2-1 cluster of primary glioblastomas (K3-1, with 18 of 20 primary glioblastoma; blue bar, Fig. 3A ). Viewing the individual gNMF components (Fig. 3B) indicates that assignment to K3-1 is driven by gains Figure 3 . NMF using rank K = 3. A, heat map plot (see Fig. 2 ) for rank 3 clustering shows preservation of primary/secondary division while also identifying two subgroups of secondary glioblastoma. Secondary glioblastoma clusters are significant by permutation testing (P < 0.01; see Results). B, the individual components from NMF, K = 3, converted to gain/loss representation. Components represent the CNA pattern that defines cluster assignment, with gain/loss shown as red/green, respectively. of chromosome [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] , and 20 and a small region of chromosome 12, as well as loss of chromosome 10 and smaller regions of 9 and 11, features typical of primary glioblastoma. Notably, the K3 classification reveals two distinct subclasses of secondary glioblastoma: K3-3 is dominated by regions of loss, in particular on chromosomes 6, 9, 10, 13, 18, and 19, whereas K3-2 has prominent regional gains on chromosomes 4, 8, and 12 and focal gains on ch7 and ch11.",
